BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
First simplify each equation and add/subtract terms so that each equation is in standard form. This gives

[`\newcommand{\amp}{&}\left\{
                  \begin{alignedat}{4}
                  \amp [$f[2]] \\
                  \amp [$f[3]]
                  \end{alignedat}
                  \right.
                `]

We can multiply the [$nth] equation by [`-[$k]\text{,}`] and then add the sides of each equation to eliminate [`[$eliminated]\text{.}`] This leaves the equation [`[$sol[0]]=[$sol[1]]`] which allows us to find [`[$sol[2]]\text{.}`] From here, substitute this into any of the previous equations that still have both variables to find [`[$sol[2]]\text{.}`]

